{{short description|paper, thicker and more durable than normal writing or printing paper}}
{{redirect|Pasteboard|the software tool|Clipboard (computing)}}
{{Globalize/US|date=June 2013}}
[[Image:Coloured, textured craft card.jpg|thumb|250px|Card stock for [[craft]] use comes in a wide variety of textures and colors.]]
[[File:Art of Bookbinding p239 Oscar Friedheim.png|thumb|An Oscar Friedheim card cutting and scoring machine from 1889]]
'''Card stock''', also called '''cover stock''' or '''pasteboard''', is a [[paperboard|paper stock]] that is thicker and more durable than normal writing or printing [[paper]], but thinner and more flexible than other forms of [[paperboard]]. 

Card stock is often used for [[business card]]s, [[postcard]]s, [[playing cards]], catalogue covers, [[scrapbooking]], and other uses which require higher durability than regular paper. The texture is usually smooth, but can be textured, metallic, or glossy. When card stock is labeled as '''cover stock''' it often has a coated finish on one side or both sides (''C1S'' or ''C2S'', for "coated: one side" or "coated: two sides") to produce a glossy look and smooth texture, especially in use for the printing of business cards and book covers.<ref name="Paper Weight, Paper Size, Coated Paper, Matte Paper">{{cite news|title=Paper Weight, Paper Size, Coated Paper, Matte Paper|url=http://www.printindustry.com/Newsletters/Newsletter-40.aspx|newspaper=Printing Industry Exchange, LLC|date=Nov 2004}}</ref>

==Measurements==
Most countries use the term [[grammage]] to describe the weight of the paper in grams per square metre.  The term ''card stock'' is used to describe paper with weights from 50&nbsp;lb to 110&nbsp;lb (about 135 to 300&nbsp;g/m<sup>2</sup>).<ref name="Paper Weight Demystified">{{cite web|title=Paper and Card Stock Comparison Chart |url=https://blog.thepapermillstore.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/04/paperweightsdemystified_11.pdf|work=The Paper Mill Store |date=1 March 2018}}</ref> Alternatively, grammage can be expressed in terms of the weight per number of sheets, [[Paper density#Basis weight|pound weight]] – the weight of 500 sheets of {{convert|17|by|22|in|mm|0|abbr=on}} paper.{{cn|date=January 2016}}<ref>This differs from how text stock is determined, which assumes 500 sheets of {{convert|20|by|38|in|mm|0|abbr=on}} paper.{{cn|date=January 2016}} Because of the difference in the way text and card stock pound weight is determined, a sheet of 65# card stock is actually thicker and heavier than a sheet of 80# text.{{cn|date=January 2016}}</ref> 

In the U.S., card stock thickness is usually measured in ''[[thou (length)|point]]s'' or ''mils'' which is the thickness of the sheet in [[Thousandth of an inch|thousandths of an inch]]. For example, a 10 pt. card is {{convert|0.010|in|mm|3|abbr=on}} thick (roughly corresponding to a weight of 250&nbsp;g/m<sup>2</sup>), and 12 pt. is {{convert|0.012|in|mm|4|abbr=on}}. The U.S. Card Stock Thickness Point size is 0.001"<ref>
[http://www.paper-paper.com/weight.html "Let's End the "Paper Weight" Confusion"].
</ref> – not to be confused with [[Point (typography)|typographical point size]], where 1 point = 1/ 12 traditional [[Pica (typography)|pica]] = exactly 0.01383 [[inch]] = 0.35136&nbsp;mm.

[[Paper sizes]] using the [[ISO]] system are often used for card stock. Card stock sizes can be labeled as A3 (420 &times; 297&nbsp;mm or 16.5 &times; 11.7&nbsp;in) referencing the ISO Standard system, instead of using the physical dimensions to describe its size.<ref name="Paper Sizes">{{cite web|title=Paper Sizes|url=http://www.papersizes.org/a-paper-sizes.htm}}</ref><ref name="Card Stock Weights Explained">{{cite web|title=Understanding Card Stock Weights|url=http://www.paper-papers.com/paper-weights.html}}</ref>

