{{Infobox power station | name = Jersey-Atlantic Wind Farm | name_official = | image = Atlantic-Jersey Wind Farm.jpg | image_size = | image_caption = | image_alt = | location_map = USA New Jersey Atlantic County | location_map_size = | location_map_caption = Location of Jersey-Atlantic Wind Farm in New Jersey | coordinates = {{coord|39|22|53|N|74|26|51|W|type:landmark_region:US-NJ|display=inline,title}} | coordinates_ref = | country = United States | location = Atlantic County Utilities Authority Wastewater Treatment Facility, [[Atlantic City, New Jersey|Atlantic City]], [[New Jersey]] | status = O | construction_began = | commissioned = March 2006 | decommissioned = | cost = US$12.5&nbsp;million | owner = Jersey-Atlantic Wind, LLC | operator = | ps_units_operational = 5 x 1.5&nbsp;[[Megawatt|MW]] | ps_units_manu_model = [[General Electric]] | wind_hub_height = {{convert|262|ft|m|abbr=on|0}} | wind_rotor_diameter = {{convert|240|ft|m|abbr=on|0}} | wind_rated_speed = {{convert|13|–|15|mph|abbr=on|0}} | wind_farm_type = onshore | wind_site_elevation = | wind_site_usage = | wind_site_area = | ps_electrical_capacity = 7.5 [[Megawatt|MW]] | ps_electrical_cap_fac = | website = | extra = }}
The '''Jersey-Atlantic Wind Farm''' in [[Atlantic City, New Jersey|Atlantic City]], in [[Atlantic County, New Jersey|Atlantic County]], [[New Jersey]], is the first coastal [[wind farm]] in the United States and the first wind farm in New Jersey. It became operational in March 2006<ref name="Infigen Energy">{{cite web|title=4th Annual Australian Microcap Investment Conference|url=http://www.infigenenergy.com/media/docs/Presentation-to-the-Australian-Microcap-Investment-Conference-8a218fe5-292a-416b-865c-e9ba66dcfa40-0.pdf|work=Infigen Energy website|publisher=Infigen Energy|pages=28|date=22 October 2013|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131029191856/http://www.infigenenergy.com/media/docs/Presentation-to-the-Australian-Microcap-Investment-Conference-8a218fe5-292a-416b-865c-e9ba66dcfa40-0.pdf|archivedate=29 October 2013|df=}}</ref> and consists of five 1.5 [[Megawatt|MW]] turbines built by [[General Electric]]. Each wind turbine reaches a height of {{convert|380|ft}}.<ref>{{Cite web|title=Atlantic-Jersey Wind Farm |publisher=Atlantic City Utilities Authority |url=http://www.acua.com/acua/uploadedFiles/Home/ACUA_Information/Files/Fact_Sheets/windfacts06.09.pdf |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111007150937/http://www.acua.com/acua/uploadedFiles/Home/ACUA_Information/Files/Fact_Sheets/windfacts06.09.pdf |dead-url=yes |archive-date=2011-10-07 |format=PDF |accessdate=2011-05-27 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/2006/11/03/nyregion/nyregionspecial2/05Rwind.html?scp=20&sq=wind%20power%20new%20jersey&st=cse | work=[[The New York Times]] | first=John | last=Rather | title=Is the Answer Blowing in the Wind? | date=2006-11-03}}</ref>
The wind farm is located at the [[Atlantic County Utilities Authority|Atlantic County Utilities Authority (ACUA)]] Wastewater Treatment Plant on [[U.S. Route 30 in New Jersey|US 30]] and is visible from highways approaching [[Atlantic City, New Jersey|Atlantic City]]. The treatment plant uses approximately 50% of the wind-generated capacity from the wind turbines, providing about 60% of the wastewater plant's electricity needs, with the remaining energy being provided to the main power grid for resale as premium renewable electricity.
