A '''very long chain fatty acid''' (VLCFA) is a [[fatty acid]] with 22 or more carbons.  Their biosynthesis occurs in the [[endoplasmic reticulum]].<ref>Jakobsson, Andreas; Westerberg, Rolf; Jacobsson, Anders "Fatty acid elongases in mammals: their regulation and roles in metabolism"  Progress in Lipid Research 2006, volume 45, pp. 237-249. {{DOI|10.1016/j.plipres.2006.01.004}}</ref>  VLCFA's can represent up to a few percent of the total fatty acid content of a cell.<ref>"Very-long-chain fatty acids from the animal and plant kingdoms" Rezanka, Tomas Progress in Lipid Research 1989, volume 28, pp. 147-87.  {{DOI|10.1016/0163-7827(89)90011-8}}</ref>

Unlike most fatty acids, VLCFAs are too long to be metabolized in the [[mitochondria]], and must be metabolized in [[peroxisome]]s.

Certain peroxisomal disorders, such as [[adrenoleukodystrophy]] and [[Zellweger syndrome]], can be associated with an accumulation of VLCFAs.<ref name=x-ald>{{cite web|last=Kemp|first=Stephan and Watkins, Paul|title=Very long-chain fatty acids|url=http://www.x-ald.nl/biochemistry-genetics/vlcfa/|publisher=X-ald Database|accessdate=5 January 2013}}</ref><ref name=vlcad-def>{{cite web|title=Very long-chain acyl-CoA dehydrogenase deficiency|url=http://ghr.nlm.nih.gov/condition/very-long-chain-acyl-coa-dehydrogenase-deficiency|publisher=Genetics Home Reference, National Institutes of Health|accessdate=5 January 2013}}</ref>

